Gauteng health officials are aiming to criss-cross every region to screen people - in a bid to fight the spread of COVID-19. So far, more than 1.2 million have been screened in Gauteng. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Over 1.2 million people have been screened in Gauteng. Gauteng health officials are aiming to criss-cross the province to screen people - in a bid to fight the spread of COVID-19. READ: COVID-19: App helps keep Gauteng residents informed On Monday, officials were in Sandton, one of the hotspots, which falls under Region E in Johannesburg. Recent data shows that out of 788 confirmed cases in Johannesburg, 248 are from the region. The City of Joburg's Mogeru Morewane says, "We have got 17 teams that were deployed across this region, the majority went to Sandton, Malboro and Bryanston and we want to lockdown the region to understand the dynamics of the disease." This proactive approach from authorities has been a welcomed move. READ: Gauteng bolsters health system in fight against COVID-19 Government says it will cast the net wide to include more people. The targeted group of people include those with flu-like symptoms, senior citizens and those with chronic medical conditions. Watch the video above for more on this story.  - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.